The class average was B+. My profs were Elise K. Burton, Karina Vold in fall, and on acorn it says that the winter’s prof is Cory Lewis. description:
I took CLA204 last semester with professor Watton and it was great. Lectures were excellent and while there were a lot of readings honestly you can get by with only about half of them since he did a great job reviewing them in the lectures. Since there was pretty much no weekly graded work, it makes the class very light during the year but stressful during midterm and exam season, but over all I'd say very easy overall. 
 
 I took CLA204 over the summer, it was all essay / writing assignments with a writing based exam. Definitely a pretty bird course (in my opinion). The only thing that I was 'stressed' about was completing the readings which you can basically find summaries for. Ended with a 95.

title: Introduction to American Literature
description: Not in an english post but I took eng250. I absolutely loved it. Our readings were selections from Norton's Anthology of American Literature Shorter 7th Ed. (and it had ~3000 pages!) and three other novels (by Faulkner, Jewett and Willa Cather). I can't remember exactly what the evaluations were since it's been a while but I think we had two close reading assignments and an essay. The Prof was absolutely amazing! Class was more like a discussion where he would have selected points for the reading and have the class give their input. I think his name is Alexander Hollenberg. Oh also I think ~10% went to participation marks.

title: Introduction to Environmental Studies
description: I took the course back in 2018 and it was pretty easy. There weren’t any tutorials or papers to write. The marks consist of 6 quizzes, that are for completion marks (however they were extremely easy and based entirely on the readings), as well as either 2 tests and a final exam. Simon Apolloni was a great professor, he was passionate the topic and led an entertaining lecture.

title: Multidisciplinary Perspectives on Environment
description: I think anyone in any discipline could get something out of it. Environmental issues are so multi-faceted and you have to consider science, policy, economics, ethics and much more. I think you'll learn things that are 'useful', and the courses will challenge your views, no matter what you currently think about the environment. 221 was taught by a conservative prof for me, that was an interesting perspective.

There were two essays, one was about comparing the research design of three different articles and the other one was about developing my own research proposal. I ended up with 82% in that course and I did not put much effort into it. You also do not need much ggr background in the course as the course is generally focusing on the research methodology itself. Ggr is kinda the theme throughout the course, which you do not need much technical knowledge about it.

The Science of Human Nature
description: I took HPS110 this past semester (Winter 2019) with Profs Vicedo and Solovey. Super birdy, course was divided as each week talking about a different aspect of human nature ex authority, discipline, aggression, etc with the topic being explained by a famous experiment like the Stanford Prison Experiment, Milgram's shock experiment etc. There was one essay assignment, one midterm and the final, which are very easy if you do the readings and focus on the questions and themes discussed in tutorial. A list of midterm and final questions were given to us in advance where they chose like 3 from. So, really straightforward and pretty birdy in my experience!

title: How to Think about Science
description: 120 was a pretty easy course when I took it. Hard to get A+, but an A is totally doable with moderate effort. Workload is pretty light. If I recall correctly, the class had one midterm, one final, one essay (1500 words I think) and a tutorial participation grade. The midterm was pretty easy (most of the class left early) and the final was almost identical to the one in the exam repository. The essay was graded quite leniently, so you don't have to stress about it. Tutorial is basically free marks for showing up (I was late to all of them and still got like 8/10 for it). There's weekly readings, but you can do well without reading them if you grind past exams (I wish I knew this earlier). I found the content quite interesting for the first half. The class looks at science from a philosophical perspective, which is something that isn't done in high school. Didn't really enjoy the second half though because it was more biology focused (topics like evolution).

title: Technology in the Modern World
description: Took it in 2023 fall with prof Adrien Zakar. Super chill course, 20% free attendance marks for weekly lectures and tutorials where you can leave after signing the attendance sheet. Only 2 essays (10% and 30%) and 1 final exam (40%). The essays were chill and they marked these essays really chill. The final covers everything mentioned in the lectures so just make sure you at least know the terms and the stories behind them. They also provide a summary of everything you need to know so you can just grind them before the exam.

description: This course is pretty interesting but it looks like this course will be very focused on a Eurocentric philosophical perspective on politics and religion. There will be readings on John Locke, Emanuel Kant, Mary Wollstonecraft, and there are more but I forgot. If you want a class that discusses more of various religions and religious practices this is not the class. So far the prof seems very nice he says he has a hard time with technology but for the most part he's able to do what needs to be done. In my personal opinion the lecture was a bit boring because it was going over the readings so if you read you didn't need to listen to be honest. But this course should be fairly straightforward and not too hard there aren't any test or quizzes just assignments that are 3-4 pages double spaced answering questions. I hope this helped.
